Saftu says the country needs a Marshall Plan on unemployment. Saftu general secretary, Zwelinzima Vavi says President Cyril Ramaphosa should include unions in finding a way forward. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Saftu says South Africa needs a Marshall Plan on unemployment. The union federation says government must accept the country is in crisis and come up with a plan to grow the economy. Saftu general secretary Zwelinzima Vavi says President Cyril Ramaphosa should include unions in finding a way forward. READ: SA's unemployment rate now at 29% South Africa's unemployment shot up to 29-percent, the highest rate since 2008. “When we saw the figures yesterday, overly they were devastating. Our correction to you is that we talking 38.5-percent,” he said. WATCH: Cosatu blames current leadership for SA's unemployment crisis “So far we are tinkering around the crisis. We've not ever, in 25-years gone into the crisis and say these are the decisive types of steps we need to take to get out of this situation.”